Per CONF-789 we can now display select boxes in a template by using:
@var|list(option1, option2, option3)@

The list, however, breaks when the options contain spaces or forward slashes. It displays the "list(...)" portion as text instead.

Basically,

@dept|list(Accounting, Customer Service)@

will show up on the page as

list(Accounting, Customer Service)

There may be other characters that break the select box, but those are the two I can confirm.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Server*. Using *Confluence Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFCLOUD-2370].
  {panel}

Would be nice to be able to show or hide templates to the end user. Right now a space admin can only hide a template by deleting it. Same with confluence-admins and global templates. A simple checkbox ought to cover it.

We have a confluence page with an {rss:} macro which references an external rss feed of our build machine's activities.  This allows those who haven't got on the rss feed bandwagon to use confluence to see what builds have been run.

Users like me, however, use an rss reader to keep up with the build info and with confluence.  Unfortuntely, my Rss reader almost always says there is something new in Confluence, since Confluences Rss feed gets updated whenever the build's rss feed updates.

So, what I really want is an Rss feed from confluence that reports changes to page *source* not changes to what gets rendered.   Some other macros that dynamically produce rendered output work "right", for instance {content-by-user}

